         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Kāśyapa says: «Good ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the magic circle of the ... sun.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... and [you] (have seen?) the moon [and] <hi>rohiṇī</hi> ... very much ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... through the Buddha ... tuberculosis illness ... over ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">Lower (of side a) left part of a leaf. The left margin is preserved in a3 and b1.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment"><hi>ṣ·</hi>: <hi>ṣ(a)</hi> can be excluded grammatically. As palaeographical possibilities remain, then, <hi>ṣ(e)</hi> and <hi>ṣ(i)</hi>, of which the latter is the only ending that makes sense grammatically: without doubt an adjective in <hi>-ṣi</hi> modifying <hi>koññäktes</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
